title: Israeli satire program brutally mocks Gaza Greta's flotilla
description: Greta Thunberg has been utterly humiliated as part of an Israeli satire show making fun of her flotilla to Gaza.  Israel’s number one satire program, Eretz Nehederet, mocked the Swedish activist in its latest English-language skit.  The parody follows Thunberg and other anti-Israel activists sailing to Gaza’s shores in the distance but then finding out about the ceasefire between Israel and Hamas.  Thunberg’s character reacts angrily to the news of the ceasefire because she can no longer protest about it.  This comes as the International Court of Justice ordered Israel to permit UN aid efforts in Gaza.

title: John Fetterman savagely breaks with Democrats over Government shutdown
description: Democratic Senator John Fetterman has broken ranks with the Democrats to vote with Republicans to avoid prolonging a government shutdown.  The US government shutdown has now reached one of the longest in US history as Democrats and Republicans battle over healthcare funding.  Fetterman and a few other lawmakers broke ranks with the party, voting with Republicans to reopen the government.  The Senate failed to advance a Republican bill to pay federal workers during the shutdown, falling short of 60 votes with a 54-46 vote.  Three Democrats, including John Fetterman, voted with the Republican Party.

title: Duke the Collie wins Australia's hardest working dog | 7NEWS
description: Duke the Collie from Stonehenge in Central Queensland has won Australia's Cobber Challenge, running 556 kilometres over three weeks to claim first prize. He becomes only the second Collie to win the prestigious working dog competition in its 10-year history. Owner Beck Smith runs her property largely alone and credits her working dogs with helping her through tough times, including recovery from catastrophic flooding earlier this year. title: Jamaica Braces For Hurricane Melissa As It Strengthens To Category 4 Storm | 10 News
description: Hurricane Melissa has strengthened into a major Category 4 hurricane as it inches closer towards Jamaica.  The US National Hurricane Center has warned of catastrophic flash flooding and landslides across portions of southern Hispaniola and Jamaica, with torrential rains of up to 760 millimetres expected.  People on the island are being urged to seek shelter immediately, with the possibility of Melissa intensifying to a Category 5 storm on Sunday night, and likely to reach the southern coast of Jamaica as a major hurricane late Monday or Tuesday morning. title: New book drops bombshell allegation Ghislaine Maxwell performed sex act on George Clooney
description: Virginia Giuffre’s new memoir has shockingly alleged that convicted sex trafficker Ghislaine Maxwell performed a sex act for actor George Clooney.  Giuffre’s memoir ‘Nobody’s Girl’ was released posthumously on October 21, following the 41-year-old’s death earlier this year.  The former victim of paedophile Jeffrey Epstein reiterated claims that Maxwell allegedly boasted about her past romps, but claimed it may or may not have been true.  “Whether that was true or not, we’ll never know,” the memoir read.  The allegation involving the sex trafficker and A-list actor follows a claim that Clooney and Maxwell became intimate in a bathroom at a party.

title: ‘Uncomfortable situation’: Australia braces for a ‘material upside shock’ to inflation
description: Barrenjoey Chief Economist Jo Masters claims a “material upside shock” to inflation is expected ahead of the release of the CPI September quarter report.  “We’ve got a forecast of 0.9 per cent inflation on that trimmed mean basis in the quarter,” she told Sky News Australia.  “It’s an uncomfortable situation where inflation looks like it’s accelerating a little bit, and that acceleration is coming largely from housing-related inflation.”

title: Donald Trump’s deadline for Hamas to return hostage bodies looms
description: The deadline looms after US President Donald Trump gave Hamas 48 hours to return the deceased hostages.  Trump took to his social media platform, Truth Social, to issue an ultimatum to Hamas over the return of the hostages on Saturday.  The president has denied on more than one occasion that the US will put boots on the ground in Gaza, but Trump says there are military forces in the region who could intervene.  Trump's comments come as 13 hostages remain in Gaza, following the recent release of the living hostages.  Following the signing of the peace plan, reports arose of Hamas killing people in Gaza. Sky News host Chris Kenny comments on a video released by Israel showing violence by Hamas.  For more Hamas' violent actions following the signing of the peace agreement, Sky News host Sharri Markson was joined by Israeli News Anchor Lital Shemesh.  WARNING: Distressing content.

title: Egyptian excavators enter Gaza to find Israeli hostage bodies | ABC NEWS
description: Israeli authorities have allowed an Egyptian excavation team to enter Gaza through the Rafah border crossing to find the bodies of deceased Israeli hostages.  The team will work with Red Cross to locate the remains under rubble and will operate inside Israel’s yellow line. Israel is accusing Hamas of deliberately delaying the return of hostage bodies. The Israel-Hamas ceasefire appears to be holding despite several Israeli strikes on targets deemed to be threats to Israeli security. Meanwhile, Israeli media is describing US officials’ consistent visits to Israel as ‘Bibi-sitting’, suggesting Washington is actively deterring the Israeli Prime Minister from reigniting the Gaza war. The Israeli leader has rejected the suggestion.  Subscribe: http://ab.co/1svxLVE  ABC NEWS provides around the clock coverage of news events as they break in Australia and abroad. title: Foreign e-commerce platforms threatening Australian retail sector
description: Australia's biggest retailers are warning that more businesses will fold if foreign owned e-commerce platforms are allowed to keep operating with less regulation as they are creating an "uneven playing field".  Chinese-owned Temu and Shein are leading the way when it comes to the rapid growth of foreign-owned e-commerce platforms.  This is concerning leaders within the $430 billion Australian retail sector, which is our largest private sector employer, supporting 1.4 million Australians' jobs.

Additional smart gates are also being installed to speed up the arrival process for returning passengers. title: US government shutdown affecting air travel amid staffing shortages
description: The near-month-long government shutdown in the United States is affecting air travel.  Safety concerns are rising after airports across the country report major staffing shortages.  This comes as thousands of flights have been delayed as airports across the country deal with staffing shortages.  TSA agents and air traffic controllers are still required to show up to work due to being an essential employee, despite not getting paid, due to the government shutdown.  However, many employees are having to call out sick because they say they can’t afford to pay for things such as gas and childcare costs.  Since the shutdown began at the start of October, more than 250 Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) facilities have reported staffing problems.

title: Trump heads to Japan after inking deals with ASEAN nations | ABC NEWS
description: US President Donald Trump is headed to Japan after signing a swathe of trade deals with South East Asian nations at the ASEAN summit. The US leader also witnessed the official signing ceremony of a Thailand-Cambodia peace treaty alongside Malaysian Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim in Kuala Lumpur.  Mr Trump is scheduled to meet with newly-appointed Japanese Prime Minister Sanae Takaichi before attending the APEC Summit in South Korea.  Meanwhile, US Treasury Secretary Scott Bessent and Chinese Deputy Premier He Lifeng have agreed to a framework for anticipated trade talks between President Trump and his Chinese counterpart Xi Jinping. title: Louvre heist suspects arrested but whereabouts of jewels unclear | ABC NEWS
description: Two suspects have reportedly been arrested over a brazen robbery at the Louvre Museum in Paris.  The Paris prosecutors’ office confirmed one man was restrained in handcuffs at an airport before boarding his flight to North Africa.  French authorities say the suspected thieves have criminal backgrounds and have been linked to burglaries in the past.  The whereabouts of eight items of precious jewellery remain unknown after nine crown jewel pieces were initially removed from the Apollo Gallery at the museum, which houses the world-famous Mona Lisa.
